26 PART IV. HURRICANE RECOVERY AND RESILIENCE
27 SECTION 4.1.(a) There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Department
28 of Public Safety, Office of Recovery and Resiliency (NCORR) the nonrecurring sum of one
29 hundred fifty million dollars ($150,000,000) for the 2025-2026 fiscal year to be allocated and
30 used as follows:
31 (1) One hundred million dollars ($100,000,000) to establish an emergency
32 housing response fund available to NCORR to respond to housing needs after,
33 and due to the event on which is based, a major disaster declaration by the
34 President of the United States under the Stafford Act (P.L. 93-288). The State
35 Building Code Council shall adopt rules establishing an expedited permitting
36 process and code flexibility for like-for-like disaster rebuilding.
37 (2) Fifty million dollars ($50,000,000) to establish a voluntary buyout fund.
38 Moneys in the fund shall be used to purchase homes undergoing, and located
39 in areas subjected to, repeated flooding due to natural disasters. NCORR may
40 purchase a qualifying home for up to one hundred ten percent (110%) of the
41 pre-disaster fair market value of the home.
42 SECTION 4.1.(b) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025.
43 SECTION 4.2.(a) The Department of Insurance shall study the feasibility, and the
44 best method of implementing, a low-interest loan program to provide loans to homeowners for
45 costs associated with strengthening residential structures to withstand hurricanes. As part of its
46 study, the Department shall investigate and recommend optimal loan terms, the administrative
47 structure for the program, and limitations on loan amounts and on uses of loaned funds necessary
48 to maximize safety and economic benefits and target funding support where need is greatest. The
49 Department, as a further part of the study, shall include whether, and to what extent, to use loans
50 to do one or more of the following: (i) supplement a quality wind-mitigation inspection by a
51 licensed home inspector, (ii) create a report for the homeowner resulting from the inspection that
Page 8 DRS45326-MCxf-177

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 provides information to contractors and insurance companies of recommended improvements
2 that will best improve and contribute to storm readiness and resilience, and (iii) offset the costs
3 to homeowners of best practices for home improvements for storm resilience by licensed
4 contractors, including, but not limited to, strengthening roof-to-deck attachments, reinforcing
5 roof-to-wall connections, installation of secondary water resistance for roofs, window upgrades,
6 and exterior door upgrades. In addition, the Department shall determine and make
7 recommendations on appropriate levels of discounting insurance rates to further effectively
8 incentivize homeowners to undertake implementation of identified enhanced resilience
9 improvements for homes. The Department shall submit its report, including funding needs and
10 any legislative proposals, to the General Assembly and the Fiscal Research Division no later than
11 January 1, 2026.
12 SECTION 4.2.(b) This section is effective when it becomes law.
13
14 PART V. HOUSING AFFORDABILITY AND FINANCING MECHANISMS
15 SECTION 5.1. The Housing Innovation Office established by the Housing Finance
16 Agency pursuant to Section 1.1 of this act shall study methods of incentivizing the construction
17 of, and increasing the affordability of, housing options for rent or sale. As part of its study, the
18 Office shall examine tax incentives to developers of, and renters and purchasers of, low-income
19 housing; tax increment financing options; local and State bonding initiatives; public private
20 partnerships to engage and maximize State or local dollars with private philanthropy; and any
21 other financial, regulatory, or compliance measures the Office determines can reasonably be
22 expected to increase the availability and affordability of low-income housing. The Office shall
23 submit its report, including funding needs and any legislative proposals, to the General Assembly
24 and the Fiscal Research Division no later than January 1, 2026.
25 SECTION 5.2. Beginning January 1, 2025, and at least once every biennium
26 thereafter, the State Auditor shall audit all housing programs administered a State agency having
27 an annual budget of ten million dollars ($10,000,000) or more.
28 SECTION 5.3. This Part is effective when it becomes law.
29
30 PART VI. ADAPTIVE REUSE AND CONVERSION
31 SECTION 6.1.(a) Article 4 of Chapter 105 of the General Statutes is amended by
32 adding a new section to read:
33 "§ 105-153.14. Credit for short-term rental conversion to affordable housing.
34 (a) Credit. – An owner of a hotel or motel providing lodging accommodations for pay
35 located in this State with at least 30 rooms for short-term rental is allowed a credit against the tax
36 imposed by this Part for each affordable rental unit created from the conversion of one or more
37 rooms. The amount of the credit is equal to the lesser of (i) thirty percent (30%) of the cost of
38 conversion or (ii) forty thousand dollars ($40,000). The credit is allowed for the taxable year
39 within which the conversion is completed.
40 (b) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
41 (1) Affordable rental unit. – A rental unit used as a permanent residence by an
42 eligible renter and subject to permanent affordability restrictions.
43 (2) Eligible renter. – An individual who occupies the affordable rental unit as a
44 primary residence and is a person of lower income, as defined by G.S. 157-3
45 (3) Permanent affordability restrictions. – Restrictions that have been
46 permanently imposed by the Housing Finance Agency on an affordable rental
47 units owned, operated, or managed by an appropriate nonprofit organization
48 Permanent affordability restrictions imposed or required by the Agency
49 pursuant to this subdivision may require a regulatory agreement with the
50 Agency or other affordability restrictions in recorded documents, provided the
DRS45326-MCxf-177 Page 9

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 Agency determines that such restrictions are enforceable and likely to be
2 enforced.
3 (c) Limitation. – The credit allowed by this section may not exceed the amount of tax
4 imposed by this Part for the taxable year reduced by the sum of all credits allowable, except
5 payments of tax by or on behalf of the taxpayer.
6 (d) No double benefit. – The credit allowed by this section does not apply to costs paid
7 with funds provided to the taxpayer by a State or federal agency or program. A taxpayer who
8 claims the credit allowed in this section may not, for the same activity, claim another credit
9 allowed in this Part."
10 SECTION 6.1.(b) The State Building Code Council shall adopt rules establishing
11 an expedited permitting process of no more than 45 days and code flexibility for the conversion
12 of hotel and motel rooms into affordable rental units (i) for which a tax credit is allowed under
13 G.S. 105-153.14, as enacted by subsection (a) of this section, and (ii) where the existing building
14 footprint is maintained. The flexibility allowed in this section shall not amend any provisions
15 required to maintain safety measures necessary but shall make allowances for any existing
16 structural or other constraints applicable to motels and hotels but not applicable to residential
17 structures.
18 SECTION 6.1.(c) Subsection (a) of this section is effective for taxable years
19 beginning on or after January 1, 2025. Subsection (b) of this section is effective when it becomes
20 law.
21 SECTION 6.2.(a) There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Housing
22 Finance Agency the nonrecurring sum of two million dollars ($2,000,000) for the 2025-2026
23 fiscal year to be used for an accommodation conversion program. The program, using
24 competitive application process for developers, shall provide funding to offset certain costs
25 involved in converting hotels and motels into affordable rental units for permanent housing.
26 Costs which may be offset with funding appropriated in this subsection includes architectural
27 and financial feasibility assessment assistance. The Agency shall develop an application process
28 and detailed guidelines applicable to the program to maximize the number of affordable rental
29 units resulting from the funding provided in this section.
30 SECTION 6.2.(b) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025.
31
32 PART VII. TENANT PROTECTIONS AND RENTAL AFFORDABILITY
33 SECTION 7.1(a) There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Housing
34 Finance Agency the recurring sum of thirty million dollars ($30,000,000) for each fiscal year of
35 the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium to be allocated to an Emergency Rental Assistance Fund
36 established by the Housing Finance Agency. Funds in the Emergency Rental Assistance Fund
37 shall be used to provide temporary rental and housing assistance to persons of low income, as
38 defined in G.S. 157-3, and to persons experiencing homelessness. The temporary rental and
39 housing assistance provided in this section shall be limited in duration and shall not exceed six
40 consecutive months of provided assistance for any one person or family.
41 SECTION 7.1.(b) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025.
42 SECTION 7.2.(a) G.S. 7A-451 reads as rewritten:
43 "§ 7A-451. Scope of entitlement.
44 (a) An indigent person is entitled to services of counsel in the following actions and
45 proceedings:
46 …
47 (20) Proceedings for summary ejectment actions brought under Articles 3 and 7 of
48 Chapter 42 of the General Statutes."
49 SECTION 7.2.(b) This section becomes effective October 1, 2025, and applies to
50 actions for summary ejectment brought on or after that date.
Page 10 DRS45326-MCxf-177

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 7.3.(a) Article 6 of Chapter 42 of the General Statutes is amended by
2 adding a new section to read:
3 "§ 42-57. Alternative Security Deposit Payment Options.
4 (a) Definitions. – For the purposes of this section the following definitions apply:
5 (1) Security deposit insurance. – A policy or bond issued by an insurer licensed
6 to do business in this State, which guarantees payment to the landlord for
7 damages or unpaid rent up to an amount equivalent to the security deposit
8 otherwise required under G.S. 42-50 and this Article.
9 (2) Installment payment plan. – An agreement between the landlord and tenant
10 allowing the tenant to pay the security deposit in periodic payments over a
11 specified term.
12 (b) Tenant Options. – Instead of paying the full amount for a security deposit authorized
13 by G.S. 42-50 at the commencement of the lease, a tenant may elect one of the following
14 alternatives:
15 (1) Installment payment plan. – The tenant may pay the security deposit in
16 installments pursuant to a written installment payment plan agreed upon by
17 the landlord and tenant. The plan shall include all of the following:
18 a. The total amount of the security deposit, not to exceed the amount
19 established by G.S. 42-51(b).
20 b. A payment schedule not to exceed the lease term or six months from
21 the commencement of the lease term, whichever is lesser.
22 c. Signatures of both the landlord and the tenant.
23 (2) Security deposit insurance. – The tenant may provide security deposit
24 insurance as a substitute for a cash security deposit. The insurance policy or
25 bond shall do all of the following:
26 a. Name the landlord as the beneficiary or insured party.
27 b. Remain in effect for the duration of the lease term, including any
28 renewals or extensions, unless otherwise agreed by the landlord."
29 SECTION 7.3.(b) This section is effective when it becomes law.
30
31 PART VIII. HOMELESSNESS PREVENTION AND SOLUTIONS
32 SECTION 8.1(a) There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Housing
33 Finance Agency the recurring sum of thirty-five million dollars ($35,000,000) for each fiscal
34 year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium. The Housing Finance Agency shall work with local
35 housing authorities to use the funds appropriated in this section to provide combined housing and
36 wraparound services to persons and families experiencing homelessness. For purposes of this
37 subsection, wraparound services means the collective components of comprehensive and
38 individualized support for persons with serious mental health or behavioral challenges.
39 SECTION 8.1.(b) There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Housing
40 Finance Agency the sum of twenty million dollars ($20,000,000) in nonrecurring fund to be
41 allocated to a Rapid Rehousing Program established by the Housing Finance Agency. The Rapid
42 Rehousing Program shall work with the local housing authorities to use the funds appropriated
43 in this section to provide temporary, short-term rental and housing assistance and case
44 management services to persons experiencing homelessness.
45 SECTION 8.1.(c) Notwithstanding any other provision in this section, funds
46 appropriated in this Part may also be allocated by the Housing Finance Agency to any local
47 housing authorities established under Chapter 157 of the General Statutes that request funds to
48 establish coordinated entry systems designed to ensure that all people experiencing a housing
49 crisis have fair and equal access to the rental and housing assistance provided for in this Part.
50 The coordinated entry systems shall be designed to evaluate whether a person or family is
51 qualified for the rental or housing assistance funded by this Part and shall ensure that individuals
DRS45326-MCxf-177 Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 and families are offered the most appropriate rental or housing assistance based on their needs.
2 The Housing Finance Agency shall establish guidelines and a process for applying for the funds
3 appropriated in this Part and may allocate the funds according to its discretion.
4 SECTION 8.1.(d) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025.
