6 PART IX. CONSTRUCTION WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT
7 SECTION 9.1.(a) Article 10 of Chapter 143B of the General Statutes is amended by
8 adding a new Part to read:
9 "Part 21A. Housing Advancement.
10 "§ 143B-472.124. Housing innovation and affordability advancement.
11 (a) Title. – This Part shall be known and may be cited as "The Housing Innovation and
12 Affordability Advancement Act".
13 (b) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this Part.
14 (1) Department. – The Department of Commerce.
15 (2) Construction skilled trade. – Specialized careers requiring hands-on skills and
16 training to build and maintain structures but not requiring a four-year degree.
17 The term includes electricians, plumbers, carpenters, roofers, HVAC
18 technicians, and other similar skills applicable to and used in the construction
19 of residential structures.
20 (3) Institution of higher education. – Any public university, community college,
21 or technical training school in North Carolina offering programs in
22 construction skilled trades.
23 (c) Housing Construction Development Program. – There is established in the
24 Department of Commerce the Housing Construction Development Program (Program). The
25 Program shall be comprised of the following elements:
26 (1) Workforce development. – In conjunction with The University of North
27 Carolina and the Community Colleges System Office, the Department shall
28 develop a grant program for institutions of higher education in this State to
29 expedite and facilitate the expansion of home construction skilled trade
30 training programs. The Department shall (i) develop guidelines for an
31 application process for institutions of higher education for the allocation of
32 funds granted pursuant to this section and (ii) prioritize awarding funds based
33 on the degree to which the institution has shown in the application the
34 following:
35 a. A viable plan to partner and create learning synergies with industry
36 leaders and employers to align training and real-world home
37 construction needs.
38 b. The funding will be used for home construction workforce needs,
39 including construction skilled trades.
40 (2) Apprenticeship development. – In conjunction with The University of North
41 Carolina and the Community Colleges System Office, the Department shall
42 develop a grant program for subsidizing the costs of qualifying employers for
43 paid apprenticeship positions for students in institutions of higher education
44 in the State in order to promote direct-to-hire pathways for participating
45 students to be prepared for and immediately fill home construction industry
46 workforce needs. A qualifying employer is an employer currently licensed as
47 a contractor or subcontractor to construct or perform construction skilled
48 trades in residential homes in the State. The Department shall (i) develop
49 guidelines for an application process for qualifying employers for the
50 allocation of funds granted pursuant to this section and (ii) prioritize awarding
Page 12 DRS45326-MCxf-177

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 funds based on the degree to which the employer has shown, in the application
2 or otherwise, the following:
3 a. A viable plan to partner and create learning synergies and pre- and
4 post-graduation employment opportunities for students attending
5 institutions of higher education in the State.
6 b. The funding will be used to subsidize the total cost of the paid
7 apprenticeship program created by the qualifying employer.
8 c. The funding will not exceed two thousand five hundred dollars
9 ($2,500) per participating apprentice.
10 d. A history of hiring participating apprentices and students graduating
11 in relevant fields from institutions of higher education.
12 (3) Innovation assistance. – In conjunction with The University of North Carolina
13 and the Community Colleges System Office, the Department shall develop a
14 grant program for institutions of higher education in this State to offset costs
15 of researching and developing (i) building methods that show potential to
16 reduce construction time and costs, (ii) more affordable or sustainable
17 materials, or (iii) pioneering construction techniques that save resources while
18 maintaining or improving quality. The Department shall develop guidelines
19 for an application process for institutions of higher education for the allocation
20 of funds granted pursuant to this section."
21 SECTION 9.1.(b) There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Department
22 of Commerce the recurring sum of fifty million dollars ($50,000,000) for each fiscal year of the
23 2025-2027 fiscal biennium for the Housing Construction Development Program established in
24 G.S. 143B-472.124, as enacted by subsection (a) of this section, to be allocated as follows:
25 (1) Fifteen million dollars ($15,000,000) to be used for workforce development
26 purposes, as set forth in G.S. 143B-472.124(c)(1).
27 (2) Ten million dollars ($10,000,000) to be used for innovation assistance
28 purposes, as set forth in G.S. 143B-472.124(c)(3).
29 (3) The remainder to be used for apprenticeship development purposes, as set
30 forth in G.S. 143B-472.124(c)(2).
31 SECTION 9.1.(c) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025.
32
33 PART X. FAIR HOUSING AND EQUITY
34 SECTION 10.1.(a) There is appropriated from the General Fund to the North
35 Carolina Human Relations Commission the recurring sum of three million dollars ($3,000,000)
36 for each fiscal year of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium. The funds appropriated in this section shall
37 be used by the Human Relations Commission to actively investigate, identify, and report to the
38 Attorney General discriminatory practices in the housing market that violate the State Fair
39 Housing Act.
40 SECTION 10.1.(b) There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Department
41 of Commerce the recurring sum of twenty-five million dollars ($25,000,000) for each fiscal year
42 of the 2025-2027 fiscal biennium to be allocated to a special account established by the
43 Department to be known as the Equitable Development Account. Funds appropriated to the
44 account shall be used to identify historically underinvested neighborhoods and provide funds to
45 the local government units in which identified neighborhoods are located to construct, improve,
46 and repair water, sewer, electrical, transportation, and other infrastructure. For purposes of this
47 subsection, a historically underinvested neighborhood is one that faces persistent challenges due
48 to discriminatory policies and practices resulting in limited access to resources and opportunities.
49 SECTION 10.1.(c) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025.
50 SECTION 10.2.(a) G.S. 160D-501 reads as rewritten:
51 "§ 160D-501. Plans.
DRS45326-MCxf-177 Page 13

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 …
2 (b) Comprehensive Plan Contents. – A comprehensive plan shall analyze, evaluate, and
3 require the implementation of equitable distribution of affordable housing and may, among other
4 topics, address any of the following as determined by the local government:
5 (1) Issues and opportunities facing the local government, including consideration
6 of trends, values expressed by citizens, community vision, and guiding
7 principles for growth and development.
8 (2) The pattern of desired growth and development and civic design, including
9 the location, distribution, and characteristics of future land uses, urban form,
10 utilities, and transportation networks.
11 (3) Employment opportunities, economic development, and community
12 development.
13 (4) Acceptable levels of public services and infrastructure to support
14 development, including water, waste disposal, utilities, emergency services,
15 transportation, education, recreation, community facilities, and other public
16 services, including plans and policies for provision of and financing for public
17 infrastructure.
18 (5) Housing with a range of types and affordability to accommodate persons and
19 households of all types and income levels.
20 (6) Recreation and open spaces.
21 (7) Mitigation of natural hazards such as flooding, winds, wildfires, and unstable
22 lands.
23 (8) Protection of the environment and natural resources, including agricultural
24 resources, mineral resources, and water and air quality.
25 (9) Protection of significant architectural, scenic, cultural, historical, or
26 archaeological resources.
27 (10) Analysis and evaluation of implementation measures, including regulations,
28 public investments, and educational programs.
29 …."
30 SECTION 10.2.(b) This section is effective when it becomes law.
31
32 PART XI. EFFECTIVE DATE
33 SECTION 11. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
34 law.
